Sheikh '''Mustafa Abd al-Rizq''' ({{lang-ar|مصطفى عبد الرازق}}) (1885 &ndash; 15 February 1947) was an Egyptian Islamic philosopher.<ref name="Goldschmidt2000">{{cite book|last=Goldschmidt, Jr.|first=Arthur|title=Biographical Dictionary of Modern Egypt|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=p3J6IS8t74QC&pg=PA8|accessdate=26 March 2013|year=2000|publisher=Lynne Rienner Publishers|isbn=978-1-55587-229-8|page=8}}</ref> He was born in Abu Jirj, [[Minya Governorate]].
Abd al-Rizq succeeded [[Mustafa al-Maraghi]] as [[Grand Imam of al-Azhar|rector of al-Azhar]]. His appointment encountered resistance, since he was not a member of the Council of Supreme [[ulama]]: [[Farouk of Egypt|King Farouk]] pressured for the law to be altered to allow him to assume office.<ref name="Brünner2004">{{cite book|author=Rainer Brünner|title=Islamic Ecumenism In The 20th Century: The Azhar And Shiism Between Rapprochement And Restraint|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jH5PyxCkeUkC&pg=PA131|accessdate=29 March 2013|year=2004|publisher=BRILL|isbn=978-90-04-12548-3|page=131}}</ref>
A follower of [[Muhammad Abduh]], Abd al-Rizq wanted "to prove the compatibility of traditional Islamic philosophy with the rationalism of modern thought".<ref name="NasrLeaman2001">{{cite book|author=Ibrahim M. Abu-Rabi'|editor=Seyyed Hossein Nasr; Oliver Leaman|title=Routledge History of World Philosophies: History of Islamic philosophy. Vol. 1|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dQQOAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA1088|accessdate=29 March 2013|year=2001|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-0-415-05667-0|pages=1088–1092|chapter=The Arab World}}</ref>
His brother, [[Ali Abdel Raziq]], was an Egyptian scholar of Islam, religious judge and government minister.<ref name=dict2010>Marshall Cavendish Reference. Illustrated Dictionary of the Muslim World Muslim World. Marshall Cavendish, 2010 {{ISBN|9780761479291}} p.79.</ref>
